Piston rings seal combustion gas by using the gas pressure acting above and behind each ring. This pressure forces the ring down into its groove and outward against the liner surface, closing the clearance between piston and liner and forming a dynamic seal during the stroke. The seal depends on the ring’s ability to respond instantly to pressure changes and maintain uniform contact with the liner.

Optimal sealing requires: 
- correct geometry of rings, ring grooves and the cylinder liner, ensuring proper contact and load distribution; 
- free axial and radial movement of each ring in its groove so the ring can follow piston motion without sticking; 
- clean ring grooves with correct clearances, verified through inspection, to avoid carbon packing and impaired ring mobility; 
- adequate lubrication to stabilise the oil film, limit wear and prevent scuffing, as lubrication quality directly influences the ring’s ability to maintain a tight gas seal.

These conditions ensure stable sealing, controlled wear and minimal blow-by throughout operation.
